th for each genome skim. The Jaccard index between two genome skims, J, is computed by Mash [4] efficiently using a hashing technique. We have tested our tool, Skmer, on genome skims simulated from assemblies of 90 species from two genera of insects (Anopheles and Drosophila) and across the avian tree of life. We test the accuracy of the distances computed by Skmer, and subsequently use the distances to find the exact/closest match to a query sample in a reference set of genome skims. Comparing to the other k-mer based tools, Skmer shows excellent performance in our simulation studies, especially when the coverage is below 4X [5] . Skmer makes the assembly-free approach to genome-skimming a viable alternative to the traditional barcoding. The software is made publicly available on Github (https://github.com/shahab-sarmashghi/Skmer.git).},
